<subsection xml:id="subsec-performing-chance-experiments-in-different-situations">
    <title>Performing chance experiments in different situations</title>
    <p>
        Performing chance experiments in different situations means conducting activities where the outcome is uncertain and can vary each time, allowing you to observe and analyze the probability of different events happening across various scenarios.
    </p>
    <p>
        In this section, you will perform chance experiments using a coin and a die.
    </p>
    <p>
        A coin is a small, flat piece of metal used as currency, typically with two sides, heads and tails.
    </p>
    <p>
        A die is a small, usually cube-shaped object with numbered faces used for rolling in games of chance, where each face represents a different number, typically <m>1</m> to <m>6</m> on a standard die.
    </p>
    <activity>
        <p>
            Work in groups
        </p>
        <p>
            Consider a fair coin.
        </p>
        <image source="/10 Kenya Shilling coin.jpg" width="40%">
            <shortdescription>Coin</shortdescription>
        </image>
        <p>
            <ol>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Before flipping, predict how many times you think each face (Heads or Tails) will appear if you flip the coin <m>20</m> times.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Now, flip the coin and record the actual results in the table below.
                    </p>
                    <table>
                        <title>Coin flip results</title>
                        <tabular left="medium" right="medium" top="medium" bottom="medium">
                            <row halign="center" header="yes">
                                <cell>Face</cell>
                                <cell>Tally marks</cell>
                                <cell>Actual count</cell>
                            </row>
                            <row halign="center" header="yes">
                                <cell>Head</cell>
                                <cell></cell>
                                <cell></cell>
                            </row>
                            <row halign="center" header="yes">
                                <cell>Tail</cell>
                                <cell></cell>
                                <cell></cell>
                            </row>
                        </tabular>
                    </table>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Compare predictions and actual results after each trial. 
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Repeat the experiment by flipping the coin <m>10</m>, <m>15</m> and <m>25</m> times.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Share and compare your results with other groups to identify overall trends.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
       
    </activity>
    <p>
        Learning point
    </p>
    <p>
        <ul>
            <li>
                <p>
                    <m>\textbf{Experiment}</m> is the  entire process of flipping a coin, which is considered a random event with a set of possible outcomes. 
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    <m>\textbf{trial}</m> is a single instance of flipping the coin, meaning one toss where you observe either heads or tails.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    <m>\textbf{outcome}</m> The result of a single flip, which can be either "heads" or "tails".
                </p>
            </li>
        </ul>
    </p>
